Certainly! Below is a sample shell script that you can use in Jenkins to perform a basic task, such as printing a message and listing files in a directory.

Copy the code
#!/bin/bash

# Print a welcome message
echo "Welcome to Jenkins Shell Script Execution!"

# Navigate to the desired directory (change specific directory)
cd /path/to/your/directory

# List files in the directory
echo "Listing files in the directory:"
ls -l

# Print completion message
echo "Script execution completed successfully!"

Explanation:
Shebang (#!/bin/bash): Specifies the script should be run using the Bash shell.
Welcome Message: Prints a welcome message to the console.
Navigate to Directory: Changes the current directory to the specified path.
List Files: Lists all files in the specified directory with detailed information.
Completion Message: Prints a message indicating the script has finished executing.
How to Use in Jenkins:
Create a New Job: Go to Jenkins and create a new job.
Configure Job: In the job configuration, add a build step to execute a shell command.
Paste Script: Copy and paste the above script into the shell command section.
Save and Run: Save the job configuration and run the job to see the script in action.

Feel free to customize the script according to your specific requirements!
